<div id="review_823739025" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/823739025" />
    <a title="Bonnie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1679313-bonnie"><img alt="Bonnie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1364082932p2/1679313.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/823739025?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bonnie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bonnie" href="/user/show/1679313-bonnie">Bonnie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780679416494" href="/book/show/744291.Mexico">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer823739025" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2500905165028194846">How I felt about that book varied from section to section. Ironically, the parts I liked best were the modern (or near modern since they were set in 1961) parts concerning bullfighting, of all things. I have never been interested in the sport, but these parts were so interesting that, paraphrasing what King Agrippa said to the Apostle Paul, &quot;almost thou persuadest me to see a bullfight&quot;. BUT King Agrippa never became Christian and I have no intention of seeing a bullfight. Four stars for these p</span>
  <span id="freeText2500905165028194846" style="display:none">How I felt about that book varied from section to section. Ironically, the parts I liked best were the modern (or near modern since they were set in 1961) parts concerning bullfighting, of all things. I have never been interested in the sport, but these parts were so interesting that, paraphrasing what King Agrippa said to the Apostle Paul, "almost thou persuadest me to see a bullfight". BUT King Agrippa never became Christian and I have no intention of seeing a bullfight. Four stars for these parts.<br /><br />The historical sections don't come off nearly as well, in my opinion. The best is concerned with the "Altomec" civilization preceding the conquest by Cortez. Altomec, by the way, is a term Michener uses for a composite of various tribes. Maybe this was to excuse himself from more extensive research. The part set in Spain wasn't bad and the part concerning early Spaniards in Mexico was also okay. I was not impressed by the part set in Virginia during the Civil War. After reading Michener's account, a reader might assume that the battle of Cold Harbor was fought in The Wilderness. I did like the part about unreconstructed Confederates heading for Mexico. I've read better novelizations of history. Two or maybe three stars for these parts.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2500905165028194846" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


